---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import ReplyTask from '../../../../../components/ReplyTask.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';

const brokenCode = `public record DeliveryRequest(string Item, int Quantity, string? Note);

var request = new DeliveryRequest("Notebook", "Leave at desk", 2);`;

const compilerMessages = `error CS1503: Argument 2: cannot convert from 'string' to 'int'
error CS1503: Argument 3: cannot convert from 'int' to 'string?'`;

const replyText = `[learn:csharp/008:q1]

The supplied declaration must not change:
public record DeliveryRequest(string Item, int Quantity, string? Note);

This constructor call does not compile:
var request = new DeliveryRequest("Notebook", "Leave at desk", 2);

Compiler messages:
error CS1503: Argument 2: cannot convert from 'string' to 'int'
error CS1503: Argument 3: cannot convert from 'int' to 'string?'

Write only:
A. One corrected constructor line. Do not change the record declaration.
B. One short sentence that gives the shared root cause of both errors and explains why string? does not make that position optional.
C. The resulting values of request.Quantity and request.Note.

A. Corrected constructor line:

B. Shared root cause and string? meaning:

C. Resulting values:
request.Quantity =
request.Note =`;
---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 8 · C#: positional constructor mismatch"
  heading="Find one constructor fault behind two type errors"
  lede="Read the declared positions and the compiler messages. Then repair one line and check the generated property values."
  backHref="/topics/csharp/"
  backLabel="C# sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="Read positions from left to right">
    <p>A positional record fixes the constructor order in its declaration. Each constructor argument must match the type in the same position.</p>
    <Callout>
      <code>string?</code> allows a string or <code>null</code> in that position. It does not remove the position. This constructor still needs three arguments.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The code that does not compile">
    <Code code={brokenCode} lang="csharp" />
    <p>The compiler reports two type errors:</p>
    <Code code={compilerMessages} lang="text" />
    <p>Do not treat them as two separate bugs yet. Compare argument 2 and argument 3 with the declaration first.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <ReplyTask id="learn:csharp/008:q1" difficulty={3} copyText={replyText}>
    <ol>
      <li>Write one corrected constructor line.</li>
      <li>In one short sentence, give the shared cause of both errors. Also say why <code>string?</code> does not make the third position optional.</li>
      <li>Give the resulting values of <code>request.Quantity</code> and <code>request.Note</code>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Do not change the record declaration. Write only the corrected line, one sentence, and the two values.</p>
  </ReplyTask>
</SessionPage>
